Date: 0/0/1956
Source: NZ Fishes: An Identification Guide
Author: GRAHAM
Vol / Page: 164
Edition:
Quote: HAKE or WHITING <i>Merlangius australis </i> (Hutton) Hake is [ibid. 166] known in Christchurch, and by some in Otago, as Whiting, but it is not a true Whiting. In Napier, Wellington and Marlborough the Southern Kingfish (Rexea solandri) is caught and sold as Hake. <i>Ibid.</i>315-316 SOUTHERN KINGFISH or HAKE (TIKATI) <i>Rexea solandri</i> (Cuv. and Val.) .../ This fish is known as Hake in Auckland. In New South Wales it is often caught by trawlers in one hundred and fifty fathoms and is known as King Barracouta. It is a favoured food fish. In Tasmania it is referred to as Tasmanian Kingfish.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1957
Source: Sea Anglers' Fishes of NZ
Author: PARROTT
Vol / Page: 154
Edition:
Quote: SOUTHERN KINGFISH <i>Rexea solandri (Cuv. & Val.)</i> ... The Southern Kingfish is closely related to the Barracouta, and is known in the North Island as the `hake' but this name is more accurately applied to a very different fish, <i>Merlangius australis</i>, which belongs to the true Cod family. <i>Ibid.</i> 170 Southern Kingfish Rexea solandri Hake
Notes:

